INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c04f35b3-0922-4828-8a6d-6dd7d7c98421',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Deno Lock Files & Dependency Auditing — What You Actually Need to Know$escape$,
  $escape$Deno auto-generates `deno.lock` on first run and validates it on every subsequent execution. Unlike npm's lockfile, Deno's lock file stores cryptographic hashes of every remote module — tamper with the source and the runtime refuses to execute. Lock file checks are on by default; opt out with `--no-lock` or set `"lock": false` in `deno.json`.

Versioning lives in `deno.json` under `imports` (the import map). Pin exact versions — `"oak": "jsr:@oak/oak@13.2.5"` — rather than ranges. Deno has no `node_modules` to audit, but `deno info <specifier>` resolves the full dependency graph instantly, printing every transitive dep with its resolved URL.

For security auditing, `deno check` runs type checking across the graph, and `--allow-*` flags enforce least-privilege at runtime. Check your lock file into git; a changed hash on CI is your canary for upstream supply-chain tampering. Run `deno cache --reload` to refresh and regenerate the lock file after intentional upgrades.$escape$,
  $escape$// deno.json
{
  "imports": {
    "oak": "jsr:@oak/oak@13.2.5",
    "zod": "npm:zod@3.23.8"
  },
  "lock": true
}

// Inspect full dependency graph
// $ deno info jsr:@oak/oak@13.2.5

// Reload cache + regenerate deno.lock after upgrade
// $ deno cache --reload src/main.ts

// Run with explicit permissions — no implicit network/fs access
// $ deno run --allow-net --allow-read src/main.ts$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
