INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '21ec3b2a-dfb8-43e8-8f22-2b35b01efd7c',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Deno's Concurrency Model — Event Loop, Workers, and Why You Rarely Need Threads$escape$,
  $escape$Deno runs JavaScript on a single-threaded V8 event loop backed by Tokio, Rust's async runtime. Every I/O operation — file reads, HTTP requests, DB queries — is non-blocking by default. You write async/await; Tokio handles the actual OS-level async I/O under the hood.

For CPU-bound parallelism, Deno exposes Web Workers with `new Worker(import.meta.resolve('./worker.ts'), { type: 'module' })`. Each worker gets its own V8 isolate and event loop — true OS threads, no shared heap. Communication is via `postMessage`, and you can pass `SharedArrayBuffer` with `Atomics` for lock-based coordination if needed.

Deno has no goroutines or actor model. Concurrency within a single isolate is purely cooperative — a long synchronous loop blocks everything. The pattern to internalize: keep the main thread for I/O orchestration, offload CPU work to workers. `Promise.all()` for fan-out I/O, workers for fan-out compute. `BroadcastChannel` lets multiple workers subscribe to the same named channel without wiring up individual message ports.$escape$,
  $escape$// Fan-out HTTP fetch — pure event-loop concurrency
const urls = ["https://api.example.com/a", "https://api.example.com/b"];
const results = await Promise.all(urls.map(u => fetch(u).then(r => r.json())));

// CPU-bound work — offload to a Worker
const worker = new Worker(import.meta.resolve("./hash-worker.ts"), { type: "module" });
worker.postMessage({ data: new Uint8Array(1_000_000) });
worker.onmessage = (e) => console.log("hash:", e.data.result);

// BroadcastChannel — pub/sub across all workers
const ch = new BroadcastChannel("events");
ch.postMessage({ type: "cache:invalidate", key: "user:42" });$escape$,
