INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd8a953c8-93d6-4ee1-bd31-dc2414873495',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Deno Memory Model — V8 GC, Rust Ownership, and the FFI Boundary$escape$,
  $escape$Deno's memory model spans two worlds. TypeScript code runs on V8's generational GC — allocations land in the young-generation heap, survivors promote to old-generation, and collection is automatic. Control GC pressure by preferring `ArrayBuffer` transfers (zero-copy ownership transfer) over structured clones when passing data between `Worker`s.

Beneath V8, Deno's runtime is Rust — ownership model, no GC, deterministic drops. This boundary becomes critical at the FFI layer via `Deno.dlopen`. Memory allocated by a native library lives on the C/Rust heap; V8 has zero visibility into it. `Deno.UnsafePointer` gives you a raw handle, but you own the lifetime. Skip your library's `free` equivalent and the leak is silent — no finalizer will save you.

`Deno.memoryUsage()` exposes `heapUsed`, `heapTotal`, `external` (V8-tracked native allocations), and `rss`. When `external` climbs unexpectedly, suspect un-freed FFI allocations. For hot paths, avoid allocating inside tight loops — V8's incremental GC still introduces pauses. Cap heap size in constrained environments with `--v8-flags=--max-old-space-size=512`.$escape$,
  $escape$// FFI memory lives on the native heap — V8 GC won't free it
const lib = Deno.dlopen("./libbuffer.so", {
  alloc_buf: { parameters: ["usize"], result: "pointer" },
  free_buf:  { parameters: ["pointer"], result: "void" },
});

const ptr = lib.symbols.alloc_buf(1024);
const view = new Deno.UnsafePointerView(ptr!);

// V8-managed: GC owns this
const heapBuf = new Uint8Array(1024);

console.log(Deno.memoryUsage()); // watch `external` field

// Must be explicit — no finalizer on the native side
lib.symbols.free_buf(ptr);
lib.close();$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
