INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c39b051e-02f9-47ff-a43a-fab8326a83c1',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Deno's Event Loop — How Tokio Powers Your Async Code$escape$,
  $escape$Deno's event loop is backed by Tokio, Rust's async runtime — not libuv like Node.js. This means async operations are scheduled on Tokio's multi-threaded executor, but your JavaScript still runs single-threaded on V8. When you `await` a Deno.readFile() or fetch(), control yields to Tokio, which drives I/O completion via epoll/kqueue, then wakes the V8 isolate to resume your promise chain.

The practical difference: Deno Web Workers each get their own V8 isolate *and* their own Tokio runtime slice — true parallelism without shared memory. Communication uses structured-clone via postMessage(), not shared state. For CPU-bound work, spin a Worker; for I/O concurrency, just fire multiple awaits concurrently with Promise.all().

Op registration is the bridge: every Deno built-in (network, FS, subprocess) is a Rust "op" that crosses the JS/Rust boundary zero-copy where possible, using ArrayBuffer transfer. This is why Deno's I/O benchmarks consistently beat Node on raw throughput — the op layer has lower overhead than libuv's callback dispatch.$escape$,
  $escape$// Fire concurrent I/O — Tokio drives both ops in parallel
const [file, res] = await Promise.all([
  Deno.readFile("./data.bin"),
  fetch("https://api.example.com/data"),
]);

// CPU-bound work → separate isolate + Tokio slice
const worker = new Worker(import.meta.resolve("./cpu-task.ts"), {
  type: "module",
});
worker.postMessage({ input: new Float64Array(1_000_000).fill(1.5) }, [
  // transfer buffer — zero-copy across isolate boundary
]);
worker.onmessage = (e) => console.log("result:", e.data);$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
