INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '3f9027a7-b565-400e-9704-4b06b4d08847',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Deno's Built-in Dev Toolchain: REPL, Inspector, and LSP With Zero Config$escape$,
  $escape$Deno ships a complete dev toolchain as first-class CLI commands — no separate installs, no plugin ecosystem to manage.

`deno repl` drops you into an interactive session. Pass `--eval` to pre-import modules before the prompt opens, and supply permission flags just like a normal script. JSR imports resolve on the fly: `deno repl --allow-net --eval 'import { encodeBase64 } from "jsr:@std/encoding/base64"'` gives you `encodeBase64` immediately at the `>` prompt.

For debugging, `deno run --inspect-brk main.ts` pauses execution at the first line and exposes a WebSocket endpoint. Open `chrome://inspect` and select the Deno target — full Chrome DevTools: breakpoints, call stack, heap snapshots. No launch.json required for basic use.

The LSP (`deno lsp`) is what the official VS Code extension and `nvim-lspconfig`'s `denols` preset connect to. It reads your `deno.json` for compiler options, import map, lint rules, and fmt config, giving you accurate type-checked completions across JSR, npm specifiers, and local modules — without a `node_modules` directory in sight.$escape$,
  $escape$// deno repl — pre-import before prompt opens
// deno repl --allow-net --eval 'import { encodeBase64 } from "jsr:@std/encoding/base64"'

// deno.json — single source of truth for LSP, lint, fmt, and imports
{
  "compilerOptions": { "strict": true },
  "lint": {
    "rules": { "include": ["no-explicit-any", "no-unused-vars"] }
  },
  "fmt": { "lineWidth": 100, "semiColons": false },
  "imports": {
    "@std/http": "jsr:@std/http@^1.0.0"
  }
}

// Debugger — pause at first line, attach via chrome://inspect
// deno run --inspect-brk --allow-read main.ts$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
