INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '555c8751-67b2-4d99-a091-455059180b30',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Deno's Single-Isolate Thread Model and What It Means for Horizontal Scaling$escape$,
  $escape$Each Deno process runs a single V8 isolate with one event loop thread — there is no thread pool backing `Deno.serve()` the way Node.js cluster mode works. I/O concurrency is high because the event loop never blocks, but CPU-bound work saturates that one thread immediately.

True parallelism requires explicit `Worker` instances. Each `new Worker(...)` spawns a fresh V8 isolate with its own event loop. Workers share no heap by default; you pass data via `postMessage` (structured clone) or hand off a `SharedArrayBuffer` for zero-copy coordination. `navigator.hardwareConcurrency` gives you the logical CPU count to size your pool.

For horizontal scaling across machines, Deno's stateless-by-default model is an asset: each process holds no implicit shared state, so adding replicas behind a load balancer is friction-free. Deno Deploy leans into this fully — each request can land on a fresh isolate in a different region. The implication: externalize all mutable state (Postgres, Redis, KV) from the start. Sticky sessions or in-process caches will break under replicas.$escape$,
  $escape$// Size a Worker pool to physical cores for CPU-bound work
const cpus = navigator.hardwareConcurrency;

const pool = Array.from({ length: cpus }, () =>
  new Worker(new URL("./compute_worker.ts", import.meta.url), { type: "module" })
);

let cursor = 0;
function dispatch<T>(payload: unknown): Promise<T> {
  const worker = pool[cursor++ % cpus];
  return new Promise((resolve) => {
    worker.addEventListener("message", ({ data }) => resolve(data as T), { once: true });
    worker.postMessage(payload);
  });
}

// Deno.serve stays non-blocking; heavy work goes to the pool
Deno.serve({ port: 8000 }, async (req) => {
  const result = await dispatch<string>(await req.text());
  return new Response(result);
});$escape$,
