INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '62ed18bd-7378-4d4c-9613-db36066e3d06',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Deno's Ecosystem in 2025 — JSR, npm Compat, and Long-Term Bets$escape$,
  $escape$Deno's ecosystem maturity story changed sharply with Deno 2.0 and the JSR registry. The legacy deno.land/x registry is frozen — all new packages land on jsr.io, where provenance, scoring, and TypeScript-first publishing are built in. The standard library (`jsr:@std/`) hit 1.0 across core modules (path, fs, http, assert, streams), meaning breakage risk is now low for day-to-day use.

The npm compatibility layer (`npm:` specifiers) is production-grade. You can drop in Express, Prisma, or sharp without a shim — Deno resolves them from npm's registry, applies its permission model, and types flow through automatically. This eliminates the historic "the package doesn't exist for Deno" blocker.

Community size remains smaller than Node's, but the signal-to-noise ratio is higher: Deno Deploy usage is growing, Fresh 2 ships with built-in islands, and Deno is now the runtime behind several Supabase Edge Functions. The company backing, V8 engine stability, and W3C API alignment make long-term viability credible — you're not betting on a runtime that could vanish.$escape$,
  $escape$// Mix JSR std lib + npm package — idiomatic Deno 2
import { join } from "jsr:@std/path";
import { exists } from "jsr:@std/fs";
import Anthropic from "npm:@anthropic-ai/sdk";

const logPath = join(Deno.cwd(), "logs", "run.log");

if (await exists(logPath)) {
  console.log("Log found:", logPath);
} else {
  await Deno.writeTextFile(logPath, "");
}

// npm package works with Deno's permission sandbox intact
const client = new Anthropic(); // reads ANTHROPIC_API_KEY via Deno.env$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
